%I A367070 #35 Jul 06 2026 01:04:45
%S A367070 1,16,128,250,480,864,21600,62208,73728
%N A367070 Numbers k such that k = (product of nonzero digits) * (sum of digits) for the digits of k in base 7.
%C A367070 There is a finite number of such numbers; we only calculated the terms in [1, 10^10] (Property 1' of Clerc).
%C A367070 Suppose a term k has d base-7 digits, then k > 7^(d-1), the product of nonzero digits <= 6^d, and the sum of digits <= 6*d. Since for d >= 50 we have 7^(d-1) > 6^d * (6*d), it follows that all terms are < 7^49 and thus the sequence is finite. I've further verified that there are no other terms, that is, the sequence is complete. - _Max Alekseyev_, Jul 06 2026
%H A367070 René-Louis Clerc, <a href="https://zenodo.org/records/19018760">Quelques nombres de Niven-Harshad particuliers</a>, zenodo.19018760, 2026.
%H A367070 René-Louis Clerc, <a href="https://zenodo.org/records/19020223">Nombres S+P, maxSP, minSP et |P-S|</a>, zenodo.19020223, 2026. (In French)
%e A367070 21600 = 116655_7, (1+1+6+6+5+5)*(1*1*6*6*5*5) = 24*900 = 21600.
%t A367070 Select[Range[7^7], #1 == Times @@ DeleteCases[#2, 0]*Total[#2] & @@ {#, IntegerDigits[#, 7]} &] (* _Michael De Vlieger_, Mar 25 2024 *)
%o A367070 (PARI) isok(k, b) = my(d=select(x->(x>0), digits(k,b))); vecprod(d)*vecsum(d) == k;
%o A367070 for (k=1, 10^5, if (isok(k, 7), print1(k, ", ")))
%Y A367070 Cf. A066282, A062331, A023651, A038364, A038369, A062237.
